$ initial_entry       <str> 'Parent-teacher conferences tomorrow and I keep running through the talking points in my head. Mikkel says I over-prepare but I would rather have every answer ready than stumble in front of someone asking about their child.', 'The school announced budget cuts today and there were some worried faces in the staff room. I felt steady, actually. My position is permanent and I have been here longer than most.', 'Mikkel brought up the idea of moving to Berlin again at dinner. His company has an office there and he thinks his career would grow faster in a bigger city. We have talked about this before but he seemed more serious this time.\n\nI listed the usual things: our flat is rent-controlled, my job does not transfer, we do not speak German well enough. He said we could figure it out. I said I would think about it but I have been turning it over for hours now and my stomach keeps tightening.', 'I don\'t care what Priya thinks, I handled that IV alarm correctly. The patient was stable and I had already checked the line twice before she came over to "help." I\'ve been on this unit for fourteen months now, I know the protocols.', "Still thinking about the Priya thing from earlier. I know I sounded annoyed in my last entry but there's more to it. She's been a nurse for nine years and sometimes she does this thing where she swoops in and takes over, and the doctors start looking at her for answers instead of me. I worked hard to get assigned to the step-down unit. Most new grads end up on med-surg for at least two years before they get a chance at cardiac, and I pushed for this placement because I want to be in the ICU by the time I'm twenty-five.\n\nBut here's what bugs me. When Mr. Okonkwo's wife was crying in the hallway after the cardiologist explained his prognosis, Priya was charting. I was the one who sat with Mrs. Okonkwo for twenty minutes, got her water, called her daughter. Nobody saw that. Nobody writes that in your evaluation. The doctors remember who looked competent with the IV pump, not who held someone's hand. And I did both today, but only one of those things is going to show up when they're deciding who moves to the ICU.\n\nI'm not saying Priya's a bad nurse. She's great, actually. She taught me half of what I know about reading telemetry strips. I just wish the people making decisions about my career could see the full picture instead of whatever three-second snapshot they happened to catch."
$ nudge_text          <str> 'What happens if you do stumble?', 'How did it feel watching your colleagues worry?', 'What would you need to feel okay about considering it?', 'What made her stepping in feel different from just helping out?', 'You mentioned two things you did today — the clinical work and sitting with Mrs. Okonkwo. If you had to pick one to be known for, which would it be?'
$ response_text       <str> 'Nothing dramatic, I suppose. Anyway, I should probably get some sleep instead of thinking about it.', 'A bit guilty, honestly. I knew I was safe while some of the newer teachers were clearly doing mental math about their contracts. I offered to help one of them update her CV after work, though I am not sure it made either of us feel better.', 'A guarantee, probably, and I know that does not exist. The truth is I have built everything carefully here: the job, the savings, being close to my parents. Mikkel sees possibility but I see all the things that could collapse. I do not think either of us is wrong. But I also do not know how to bridge the gap between what he wants and what I can actually handle risking.', "Because it was in front of the resident. Made me look like I didn't know what I was doing.", "Both. That's the whole point. I don't want to pick. But if I'm being honest, the Mrs. Okonkwo thing is the reason I became a nurse in the first place. The ICU stuff, the certifications — that's how you get taken seriously so you can keep doing the other part. At least that's what I tell myself."
